07332nam a22009855i 9781580466783DE-B159720240306010644.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20052005xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a97815804667837 a10.1515/97815804667832doi  a(DE-B1597)675971  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcUK 4aDD78.B55 7aSOC0080002bisacsh04a305.896/043/0904qLOC22200aNot So Plain as Black and White :bAfro-German Culture and History, 1890-2000 /ced. by Patricia Mazon, Reinhild Steingröver.31aWoodbridge, Suffolk : bBoydell and Brewer, c[2005] 1bUniversity of Rochester Press, c[2005] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (266 p.) :b17 b/w illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aRochester Studies in African History and the Diaspora ;v1900tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tForeword -- tIntroduction -- tPart I: Afro-Germans in Historical Perspective -- t1 Dangerous Liaisons: Race, Nation, and German Identity -- t2 The First Besatzungskinder: Afro-German Children, Colonial Childrearing Practices, and Racial Policy in German Southwest Africa, 1890–1914 -- t3 Converging Specters of an Other Within: Race and Gender in Pre-1945 Afro-German History -- tPart II: Cultural Representations and Self-Representations of Afro-Germans -- t4 Louis Brody and the Black Presence in German Film Before 1945 -- t5 Narrating “Race” in 1950s’ West Germany: The Phenomenon of the Toxi Films -- t6 Will Everything Be Fine? Anti-Racist Practice in Recent German Cinema -- t7 Writing Diasporic Identity: Afro-German Literature since 1985 -- t8 The Souls of Black Volk: Contradiction? Oxymoron? -- tSelected Bibliography -- tNotes on Contributors -- tName Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAn exploration of the subject of Afro-Germans, which, in recent years has captured the interest of scholars across the humanities for providing insight into contemporary Germany's transformation into a multicultural society.Since the Middle Ages, Africans have lived in Germany as slaves and scholars, guest workers and refugees. After Germany became a unified nation in 1871, it acquired several African colonies but lost them after World War I. Children born of German mothers and African fathers during the French occupation of Germany were persecuted by the Nazis. After World War II, many children were born to African American GIs stationed in Germany and German mothers. Today there are 500,000 Afro-Germans in Germany out of a population of 80 million. Nevertheless, German society still sees them as "foreigners," assuming they are either African or African American but never German. In recent years, the subject of Afro-Germans has captured the interest of scholars across the humanities for several reasons. Looking at Afro-Germans allows us to see another dimension of the nineteenth- and early twentieth-century ideas of race that led to the Holocaust. Furthermore, the experience of Afro-Germans provides insight into contemporary Germany's transformation, willing or not, into a multicultural society. The volume breaks new ground not onlyby addressing the topic of Afro-Germans but also by combining scholars from many disciplines. Patricia Mazon is Associate Professor in the Department of History at the State University of New York at Buffalo. Reinhild Steingrover is Assistant Professor in the Department of Humanities at the Eastman School of Music at the University of Rochester.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBlack peoplexRace identityzGermanyxHistory. 0aBlack peoplezGermanyxHistory. 0aBlacksxRace identityzGermanyxHistory. 0aBlackszGermanyxHistory. 4aAfrican Studies. 4aEnglish & American Literature. 4aGerman Literature. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / General.2bisacsh  aAf